[CLS] i usually go all out for the holidays to try to hide my depression every year. this year i just can't bring myself to enjoy them. i have even bought one christmas present. __end__ i can see why this time of year is difficult for you. trying to hide depression can be a challenge. rather than hiding the sadness or grieving feelings, some people find relief in acknowledging and sharing these feelings with family members who may relate. do you ever share these feelings with your cousin or grandparents that you mentioned? __end__ my cousin doesn't live around here and we have never been real close. he is alot younger than me. we just never had the connection like his sister and i did. and both my grandparents have passed away. grandpa has been gone for 12 years and grandma has been gone for 4 now. __end__ my family has always been really good about talking about our loses. things just will never be the same. __end__ i understand. when losses are experienced it is a great change in many aspects of our lives. __end__ are there any aspects of the holidays that bring you joy? maybe holiday music, movies, bright snow __unk__ if there is snow where you live ), or seeing joy on someone's face when you give them a great gift? __end__ they say it gets easier. and i agree it does. things just have changed so much. i miss how life was before i lost them. __end__ i understand - and it is normal to feel that way. when we lose someone who brought us happiness, it is only natural to miss them and their company. __end__ i love giving gifts. and i always put lots of thought into the gifts i give. my nieces and nephews can't wait every year to see what i got them. __end__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__

[CLS] i have a couch to crash on. another guy said i could store my furniture in his basement. but no official room. __end__ it's a precarious position to be in, especially during a pandemic. do you have any family members who might help? __end__ yes, i could call my mother. she has a room to stay in. but i only have the money to drive to her home, not the money for a rental truck to move all my stuff. __end__ would any family members be prepared to loan you money or a vehicle? __end__ i could ask my aunt to use her car, she has an suv, where as i drive a sedan. __end__ how much stuff do you have that needs to be moved? __end__ queen bed, bed frame, small desk, roll chair, bookshelf, rug, boxes of kitchen stuff, etc. __end__ try not to worry too much - i was in this position once myself and it did all turn out for the best though it was very scary at the time. __end__ yes, i feel almost numb from the depression. like non of my stuff matters, only that i am physically safe. __end__ [CLS] hi. yes, i'm having a hard time because last year my dad died a few days after christmas. __end__ oh i am so sorry! dealing with bereavement is hard at any time but at this time of year i think that it is even worse. __end__ when people ask about christmas plans, i don't want to depress everyone. but i can't pretend everything's okay. __end__ so you feel as though you have to avoid people because you do not want to make them feel bad that you are feeling bad? __end__ i don't know... i know my friends would be supportive. but then i feel like it's selfish of me to bring people down, when this whole year has been a downer for so many of us. __end__ well let me ask you - if the situation were reversed, would you feel that a close friend was bringing you down if they talked about their bereavement? __end__ maybe, but i wouldn't mind that. __end__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ [CLS] thank you for your time today, hearing my concerns about the future! __end__ you are so welcome. i know that you will succeed in your employment search as you have the skills and humility that potential employers are looking for. __end__ i'll continue to keep on the lookout for new job opportunities, as well as improving myself for the long term. i appreciate it! __end__ as you continue your job search, can you think of ways that you could trim your cost of living for the short term? returning to the basics for a time could help save you money while you take the next steps with your career. things like planning meals ahead of time, using items you already have instead of buying new, letting go of subscriptions you don't use daily or don't deem necessary. __end__ i could definitely reduce my spending like going out less for fast food, cutting my netflix and hulu subscriptions, and prepare my own meals for the next week weeks, as i try to find a new job. this would definitely help with my concerns about income and financial security. __end__ our lifestyle seems to be all about convenience and instant gratification, i myself being guilty of wanting those as well. but i think when we strip our needs down to the basics for a while we allow ourselves to find what is really necessary, as well as what is truly important to us. __end__ very true, people definitely need to find their fitting for when things go wrong. failure or bad events give us time to think about the important things in life, as well as our true needs. __end__ and it is important to remember that everyone goes through cycles of feast or famine, and that when you are walking through a famine you yourself are not a failure. as long as you know you are doing your best to succeed under the circumstances you have been handed, you will never truly be a failure to yourself or to others. __end__ thank you, this has really helped me overcome my anxiety and fears of the events from the past year! [CLS] you do not have to buy fancy clothes for the sake of other people! maybe you could get some counselling to work on your self esteem though? __end__ i see a counselor regularly. the sessions are virtual. i do wish there were some ways to figure out how to make the clothes i have look better or match better, be more organized with my wardrobe. i have a lot of problems with too many clothes that don't look good on me. __end__ have you tried shopping in second hand stores? you can often get some nice stuff there for cheap. __end__ but really i think that the problem is your self esteem, not what you are wearing. __end__ yes! i love second hand stores! so i should not care so much what they say about me? __end__ right! to be honest i suspect that it's far more their problem than it is yours. __end__ i agree. those women were not even in shape. they had makeup, hair done, etc., but they were not nice women. maybe they are just taking their problems and insecurities out on me. __end__ yes i think that they were. i have had issues like this myself in the past and i know how much it hurts and how hard it is to overcome it. __end__ yes. it does hurt. i want to get better at picking clothes that make me happy. a lot of my clothes are baggy. maybe i could learn to sew and alter them. __end__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ [CLS] tired, very tired!! __end__ oh? how come so tired? __end__ because i can't sleep... i don't know what's wrong with me i just lay there awake for hours! __end__ oh i have had trouble sleeping before! would you like to know what helped me? __end__ yes please, i'm desperate, i'll try anything! __end__ first of all, fixed sleep and wake times. if you toss and turn for hours, still get up at the same time. eventually your body will tire and sleeping will naturally become easier. __end__ i have to always get up for work so i am sticking to the same routines, i just lie in bed with so many thoughts racing around my head and i just can't get off to sleep __end__ second thing i do is i have a wind down routine. no work past a certain time, no matter what. only soft music, pleasant movie, some light reading, and dim the lights. it slows your body down before sleep. it will help slow that racing thoughts you are having. __end__ i did try reading a book last night, but i don't really have lights that i can dim, it's just the one bright light in our room. __end__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ [CLS] definitely you need a break, so schedule them as rewards. you can even do 15 minutes in say 4 subjects, then take a walk, take a cup of tea, or call a friend, then back to the books. __end__ keep it as simple as possible, don't get bogged down. i used to think planning was terrible< but actually, it sets one free. you feel so much better and accomplished when you see how much you have done. it really is amazing. __end__ how man classes do you have? __end__ many * __end__ i have 6 classes __end__ that's a lot but it is totally doable. here is a good example, if you plant seeds in a garden today, you have to weed it a bit tomorrow, the next day, the next day, you have to wait for rain, then weed some more, the harvest comes and yay! you are happy. but if you lie on your bed, never planting, never weeding, you procrastinate, you get nothing. __end__ if you write your classes down and then write a reasonable time to study each one. maybe 3 today, 3 tomorrow, then add rewards if you do that, maybe make a list of rewards, so you can pick and choose, then you check off when you do the subject. like a chore chart. __end__ yes haha. that is a good comparison. you have been super helpful. i will for sure try to use your advice. thank you! __end__ have a great day and thanks again __end__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__

[CLS] a second opinion is probably a good thing. i just know i can't keep laying in bed 1__unk__ 2 the day with the baby. __unk__ 6 ) __end__ yeah that you cant, and i cant stress how good it is that you realize it. i would definitely go for a second opinion. or even search for therapists that specialize in it in your area. never have been a fan of using medicine as the first go unless really needed. __end__ yeah, i'm not big on the medication. i've talked to several moms that went on it and years later had to stay on it because the withdrawals were so terrible. i'd like to be able to process through it __unk__ 7 ) __end__ and whats the worst a little talking can do for you. has talking to other moms been helpful at all? [CLS] like meditation? __end__ what am i supposed to do? just breathe in and out a lot? __end__ not exactly. controlled breathing is more of getting yourself into a quiet room. closing your eyes, and purposely and intently focusing on your breathing. slowly breathe in for a count of 5, then slowly exhale for a count of 5. repeat this process for approximately 10 minute. it will help your stress levels and help regulate your heart rate! __end__ oh i didn't know that. no, i haven't tried that. does it really work? __end__ i've been using it myself over the past 3 months and it most definitely helps! but it's absolutely imperative to clear your mind and have complete quiet. __end__ ok i can try it i guess __end__ thanks for that tip __end__ no problem. i hope this gives you some relief! stay strong! __end__ yeah, thanks. same to you __end__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__ __null__

[CLS] that is helpful information. what can i tell them? __end__ well if you can get some concrete info such as from the cdc and john hopkins showing case counts in your area. show them graphs so they can visually see the impact. also if you can get a hold of their doctor yourself, see if you can convince them to give your parents a call, say to check on them and give them some advice. __end__ that sounds like a good plan. is there anything else i can do to decrease the anxiety for me? __end__ don't get absorbed in the numbers, it can drive you crazy. also if you are using social media like twitter and getting inundated with info, remember a lot of it is fake. i would suggest limiting exposure for a little while just to get you fixed a little bit, if that makes sense. __end__ do you think there are some good social media sites that could help? __end__ not particularly social media because it open to everyone, just pick and choose where you choose to get info from. the cdc is a great resource as well as the john hopkins site which has been tracking since the beginning. everybody has a couple of news outlets they trust, use those. __end__ how can i cope with limiting my visits with my parents because i am afraid to spread covid? __end__ first of all you are not alone. but don't let them see you anxious for sure. you can also show them if they can how to do video visits. you can do that all the time, even phone calls every day. it means a lot. __end__ that makes sense. i appreciate the suggestions. how can i show them the kids care too?
